    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Ghost picking\" typically refers to items being removed from the shelf by an order picker but not recorded in the system, creating a discrepancy without stealing the goods themselves. Given your description of random small gaps in the electronics aisle that persist weekly despite good logs and security, it is highly unlikely that this is intentional sabotage or a deliberate glitch designed to hide theft, as employees would likely report the cash savings or seek compensation. The most probable cause is instead a combination of operational habitfulness, such as reordering items to trash or packaging bins incorrectly, or a subtle software logic error in the Warehouse Management System that auto-debits stock without triggering a physical count trigger for those specific slow-moving electronics.",
